":"1267","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","1287":"1287","1195":"1195","1184":"1184","environ 1180":"about 1180","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Lavieu, Loire, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Lavieu, Loire, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lavieu","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Breton   Levier   ‘helmsman’.","French: occupational name for someone who quarried a kind of flat sandstone called <i>lave</i> (from Latin <i>lapis</i>), which was used for roofing."],"variants":[{"name":"Levier","meanings":["Breton (also <b>Le Levier</b>): occupational name for a guide or sea or river pilot, from <i>levier</i> ‘helmsman’. Compare   Lavier  ."]}]},{"name":"Josserand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Henri, Pierre.","French: from an ancient Germanic personal name composed of the elements <i>gaut</i>, an ethnic name meaning ‘Goth’ or ‘Geat’ (see   Goss  ) + <i>hramn</i> ‘crow’."],"variants":[{"name":"Goss","meanings":["Short form of   Jocelyn  , also occasionally used as an independent given name. In part it may also be a revival of a medieval boy's name (  see  Joyce  ). The name is borne by the British actor  Joss Ackland  (  b. 1928 ) and the female pop singer  Joss Stone  (  b. 1987 ) as Jocelyn Eve Stoker."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Josserand IV de Lavieu was born about 1180, in Lavieu, Loire, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France, his father, Briand II de Lavieu, was 31 and his mother, Guillemette de Farnay, was 27. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Peytavine de Poitiers-Valentinois. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"environ 1180–":"umbes 1180–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","–1267":"–1267","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1210–1287":"1210–1287","1150–1184":"1150–1184","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1267":"1267","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","1287":"1287","1195":"1195","1184":"1184","environ 1180":"umbes 1180","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Lavieu, Loire, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Lavieu, Loire, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1180–":"noin 1180–Kuollut","1180